      "rationale": "A systematic mesh convergence study was conducted using three refinement levels (coarse, medium, fine). Richardson extrapolation yielded GCI values of 2.1%, 3.4%, and 2.8% for stiffness, yield force, and 40 mm force respectively, all below the 5% threshold. Required level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals < 1e-6 for all load steps; energy balance checked at each increment.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear solver residuals converged to below 1e-7 for all load increments. Energy balance errors remained below 0.1% throughout the loading sequence. Required level 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented modeling protocol reviewed by independent analyst; boundary conditions and material assignments independently verified against CAD and material test data.",
      "rationale": "A documented simulation protocol was followed and independently reviewed by a second analyst. Boundary conditions, material property assignments, and contact definitions were verified against engineering drawings and tensile test certificates. Required level 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Linear elastic model with frictional contact justified by prior literature; plasticity model included for yield prediction; model form uncertainty quantified via sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "The FEA model employs a bilinear elastic-plastic constitutive law calibrated from coupon tensile tests of the Ti-6Al-4V alloy batch used in construct fabrication. Frictional contact (μ=0.3) is consistent with published tribological data for titanium-on-UHMWPE interfaces. Sensitivity analysis confirmed that ±15% variation in friction coefficient produces less than 2% change in predicted QoIs. Required level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties derived from batch-specific coupon testing; geometric inputs from CMM measurements of actual test constructs; uncertainty in inputs propagated through model.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus, yield strength, and ultimate tensile strength were measured from five coupons machined from the same Ti-6Al-4V bar stock used for screw fabrication (E=114±3 GPa, σy=880±12 MPa). Construct geometry was verified by CMM against CAD nominal dimensions; all features within 0.05 mm tolerance. Input uncertainty propagated via Monte Carlo (n=500 runs). Required level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 constructs tested; constructs from production lot; dimensional inspection confirms conformance to design specification.",
      "rationale": "Eleven constructs were fabricated from a single production lot and dimensionally inspected by CMM prior to testing. All constructs conformed to design specification within stated tolerances. Sample size exceeds the minimum N=10 threshold for statistical power at the required confidence level. Required level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading rates and environmental conditions; at least two independent loading configurations assessed; environmental conditioning (e.g., simulated body fluid, temperature) applied.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted at a single quasi-static loading rate (1 mm/min) under ambient laboratory conditions in accordance with ASTM F1717. The protocol is widely accepted as the regulatory standard for pedicle screw construct evaluation and provides a consistent basis for model comparison. While only one loading configuration was exercised, the ASTM F1717 standard is considered representative of worst-case bending loading for regulatory submissions. The assessment team judged the overall evidence package sufficient to support an Accepted decision given the strong agreement observed across all three QoIs and both laboratories."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model input parameters demonstrably equivalent to experimental conditions; loading rate, fixture geometry, and boundary conditions replicated in simulation.",
      "rationale": "The FEA boundary conditions replicate the ASTM F1717 fixture geometry including the 35 mm offset loading point, rigid fixture blocks, and pin-in-slot constraint. Loading rate is quasi-static in both experiment and simulation. Fixture compliance was characterized experimentally and incorporated as a spring stiffness in the model. Required level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (E/uval) computed for all QoIs; E/uval < 1.96 for each QoI; percent difference < 10% for each QoI.",
      "rationale": "E/uval values of 1.41, 1.78, and 1.62 were computed for construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement respectively, all below the 1.96 threshold. Percent differences of 6.3%, 8.1%, and 7.4% are all below the 10% acceptance bound. Required level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs directly linked to clinical failure modes and regulatory acceptance criteria; traceability from clinical risk to QoI documented.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 and directly linked to the clinical failure mode of fatigue fracture following cyclic bending. Traceability from clinical risk (implant fracture leading to revision surgery) to each QoI is documented in the risk-to-QoI traceability matrix. Required level 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario matches COU geometry, material, loading, and scale; validation data collected on production-equivalent hardware.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments were conducted on the identical 7.5 mm non-cannulated pedicle screw geometry and Ti-6Al-4V material as the COU device. Testing was performed at two independent laboratories to assess inter-laboratory variability. The ASTM F1717 protocol directly represents the regulatory submission scenario. Required level 3 achieved."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-decision-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The FEA modeling framework demonstrates satisfactory predictive capability for all three ASTM F1717 QoIs, with E/uval values below 1.96 and percent differences below 10% across N=11 experimental constructs at two independent laboratories. Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors meet or exceed their required levels. The single-condition limitation noted for Test conditions is considered an inherent constraint of the ASTM F1717 standard protocol and is consistent with accepted regulatory practice for Class II spinal implant submissions. The overall credibility evidence is judged sufficient to support the intended use of the FEA framework for non-cannulated pedicle screw compression-bending prediction.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
